answer:
Solution outline

We can compute the required sum by building a trie of all strings and counting, for each trie node at depth >= 1, how many strings pass through that node (i.e., share the node's prefix). For each node with count c, there are C(c, 2) unordered pairs that share that prefix; each such node contributes exactly 1 to the longest common prefix length for every such pair. Summing C(c, 2) across all non-root nodes gives the requested total.

Algorithm

1. Create a trie where each node stores an array of 26 child indices (initialized to -1) and an integer count = 0.
2. For each input string, walk the trie from the root creating child nodes as necessary. For each character moved into (i.e., each prefix of length >= 1), increment that node's count by 1.
3. After inserting all strings, sum over all nodes except the root: total += count * (count - 1) / 2.
4. Print total.

Complexity

- Time: O(sum of lengths of strings + alphabet overhead while creating nodes). With alphabet size 26 and using arrays per node, the dominant cost is O(total characters) which is <= 3e5.
- Space: O(total characters * 26 for child indices + total characters for counts) in the worst case. With integer child indices this is acceptable within contest/server limits for the given constraints.

Correctness note

Every pair of strings contributes 1 to the sum for each prefix length they share; counting C(c, 2) at every node of depth d exactly counts how many pairs share that prefix of length d. Summing over all depths yields the total sum of longest common prefix lengths.

Reference C++ implementation

#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

struct Node {
    int nxt[26];
    int cnt;
    Node() {
        cnt = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < 26; ++i) nxt[i] = -1;
    }
};

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int N;
    if (!(cin >> N)) return 0;
    vector<string> s(N);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) cin >> s[i];

    // Preallocate nodes: at most 1 + total characters
    int total_chars = 0;
    for (auto &str : s) total_chars += (int)str.size();
    vector<Node> trie;
    trie.reserve(total_chars + 1);
    trie.emplace_back(); // root index 0

    for (const string &str : s) {
        int node = 0;
        for (char ch : str) {
            int c = ch - 'a';
            if (trie[node].nxt[c] == -1) {
                trie[node].nxt[c] = (int)trie.size();
                trie.emplace_back();
            }
            node = trie[node].nxt[c];
            trie[node].cnt += 1; // count strings passing through this node (prefix)
        }
    }

    long long ans = 0;
    for (size_t i = 1; i < trie.size(); ++i) { // skip root (depth 0)
        long long c = trie[i].cnt;
        if (c >= 2) ans += c * (c - 1) / 2;
    }

    cout << ans << '\n';
    return 0;
}

Example

For input:
3
ab abc arc

The trie counts lead to contributions: C(3,2) at prefix 'a' = 3, C(2,2) at prefix 'ab' = 1, other nodes 0. Sum = 3 + 1 = 4, matching the sample.

This implementation meets the constraints and runs in linear time in the total input size.

